      "content": "You're absolutely right! Let me explain the **EC2 Fleet approach** first, then implement it.\n\n## 🎯 EC2 Fleet Strategy\n\n**Why EC2 Fleet is Perfect:**\n\n1. **Native AWS Service**: No custom Lambda functions needed\n2. **Intelligent Failover**: Tries all combinations of instance types × AZs systematically\n3. **Immediate Failure**: Fails CloudFormation fast if NO capacity available across all combinations\n4. **Single Instance**: Perfect for our use case (target capacity = 1)\n5. **Diversified Strategy**: Spreads across AZs and instance types for maximum availability\n\n## 🔧 Implementation Plan\n\n**EC2 Fleet Configuration:**\n- **Target Capacity**: 1 (we only need 1 IDE instance)\n- **Allocation Strategy**: `diversified` (tries all combinations)\n- **Instance Types**: `m5.xlarge`, `m6i.xlarge`, `t3.xlarge`\n- **Availability Zones**: Both AZs from our VPC\n- **Launch Specifications**: 6 total (3 instance types × 2 AZs)\n\n**Failure Behavior:**\n- ✅ **Success**: If ANY combination works (e.g., t3.xlarge in AZ-b)\n- ❌ **Failure**: Only if ALL 6 combinations fail → CloudFormation fails immediately\n\n**Architecture:**\n```\nEC2 Fleet Request\n├── m5.xlarge in AZ-a\n├── m5.xlarge in AZ-b  \n├── m6i.xlarge in AZ-a\n├── m6i.xlarge in AZ-b\n├── t3.xlarge in AZ-a\n└── t3.xlarge in AZ-b\n```\n\n**Getting Instance ID:**\n- Small Lambda function to query Fleet and return instance ID\n- Much simpler than the original launcher Lambda\n- Only does lookup, no complex retry logic\n\n## 📋 Implementation Steps\n\n1. **Replace native EC2 Instance** with `CfnSpotFleet`\n2. **Configure 6 launch specifications** (3 types × 2 AZs)\n3. **Create simple lookup Lambda** to get instance ID from fleet\n4. **Keep all existing logic** (EIP, CloudFront, etc.)\n\nThis gives us the **same intelligent failover** as the original launcher Lambda, but using native AWS services with minimal custom code.\n\nLet me implement this now:"
